{
  "text": "Previous studies have suggested that S100B levels in patients treated with clozapine are increased [CITATION_1] , which in part is in agreement with the data in the current study showing raised levels of S100B in female patients treated with clozapine. The effects of clozapine are thought to be mediated primarily via antagonism at 5HT2AR and DA4R, with weak DA2R blocking activity [CITATION_2] . Astrocytes express DA2Rs and activation of these receptors using apomorphine decreases the levels of S100B in these cells, via a signalling pathway that involves inhibition of adenyl cyclase [CITATION_3] . Moreover, antipsychotic medications (such as clozapine, haloperidol and risperidone), which block DA2Rs, also decrease S100B levels [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Treatment of astrocytic C6 cells and oligodendrocytic OLN-93 cells with haloperidol and clozapine also decreases the levels of S100B [CITATION_6] . This data is in contrast with elevated levels of S100B observed in patients diagnosed with schizophrenia [CITATION_7] . However, contradictory to the hypothesis that astrocyte derived S100B levels are raised in schizophrenia, is the finding that chronic antipsychotic medication, such as haloperidol or olanzapine, reduce astrocyte numbers in Macaque Monkeys [CITATION_8] . Recent data also demonstrated that insulin downregulates levels of S100B in adipocytes (in addition to astrocytes) suggesting that other cell types may determine the levels of S100B [CITATION_9] . Interestingly, molecular links between S100B, DA2Rs and schizophrenia have been suggested where S100B has been shown to interact with the third cytoplasmic loop of the DA2R, and to enhance receptor signalling to ERK and inhibition of adenylate cyclase [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . In S100B transgenic animals, there is a decrease in the expression of DA2R suggesting crosstalk between S100B and DA2R function [CITATION_14] . Taken together, these studies support the S100B/ DA2R protein complex as a molecular target for antipsychotic medications and possible aberrant S100B/ DA2R-mediated signalling in schizophrenia.",
  "correct_citation": {
